As mentioned in the colliery notes" in the Journal of 29th
February, group shot firing with electrical fuses is somewhat uncer-
tain, and as explained in those notes, the uncertainty is due to
differences in the fuses themselves, and in the action of the current
when passing through them. There are two forms of fuses, and in
both, the fuse cap contains a small quantity of a detonating substance,

platinum wire is embedded in the detonating matter, and in the

56.Text: JULY 15, 1909.] 	QUEENSLAND GOVERNMENT MINING JOURNAL. 	371
the subjeot of a paper read by the inventor before the Chemical,
Metallurgical, aud Mining Society of South Africa on Saturday last.
After a thorough and seientifie criticism of the present methods in
use, showing through theoretical proofs, supported by practical experi-
ence, 	the 	many 	defects 	and 	accumulations 	of 	undetectable 	errors
involved, Mr. Tonnesen proceeded to describe the new system of
measuring stopes, which he walls the inclined angle method." By
means of his instrument and tape angles and distances are nreasured
directly on the inclined plane of the reef. The instrument, invented
and patented by Mr. Tonnesen, which he terms the (( Stereometer,"
is so constructed that it will measie the true inclined angle between
any three points without observing the hiorizontal and vertical angles,
no reductions or calenlations being required. It can le held-in the
hand when observing, and no oumbersome and difficult setting up is
required. It may be used for graphical records or be read by a
vernier. After a practical demonstration of the instrument, Mr
Tonnesen then showed how his method afforded a continuous and
clear manner of procedure, avoiding repeated climbing on unsafe
ground and most of the hardships met with in stope-meastring, com-
bining the advantages of the old methods with the elimination of
sources of mistakes and accumulation of undetectable errors. He
then went on to describe soms practical methods of construeting
oorrect stope plans direetly from co-ordinates and survey books
without necessitating construction of horizontal and vertical plans to
the same seale as that required for the stope plan, a correct stope
plan being of the same importance to stope measuring as the trian-
gulation system to the filling in of topographical charts. He showed
how his method affords an easy and quick check of a stope, indepen-
dent of the mine plans, and keeping within reasonable limits of
errors, as prescribed by the Mines Regulations Commission, and how,
on the other hand, tampering with the survey-pegs and marks is
easily detected and of no consequence to the measurements. In con-
clusion, Mr. Tonnesen paid a tribute to the management of the East
Rand Proprietary Mines for their liberal support and the great
interest they had taken in his endeavours.
Longwall System of Coal Mining.-Th longwall system of mining
is becoming more and more used in Continental coal mines. European
engineers contend that longwall mining reduces mineral losses to a
minimum, and affords better facilities for the application of mechani-
cal power; this latter assertion is based on the fact that the longwall
system presents a continuous working face, extending several hundred
yards in length, which simplifies the working of a mining machine,
to the one operation of undercutting the exposed seam, subsequently
admitting of its easy cleavage by hand. It is also asserted that the
longwall system as used in Europe lends itself to a more expeditious
transit of the mineral by means of coal conveyers, since temporary
tracks are readily laid along the entire length of the working face,
and the coal is often broken down into the waiting receivers, effecting
a net saving of from 12 to 15 cents per ton on all coal brought to
the surface under such conditions.- Engineering and Mining
Journal."
According to T. H. Holland, direotor, Geological Survey of
India, coal is the most valuable mineral product of India. Fully
90 per cent. of the output is consumed in developing home industry,
in 1906 the total valuation of the output at the mines being above
L1,800,000. With the exception of about 5 per cent., all the coal
produced comes from the Peninsula region, where it occurs in the
lower division of the Gondwana system. This corresponds approxi-
mately to the upper Carboniferous horizon. In other parts of India
small bodies of coal are found in rocks of Tertiary age. The eastern
Himalayan fields are the only known occurrence of Gondwana coal
not in the peninsula.
